Dynamics of Happiness

Ankita Arvind Deshmukh

05/12/2022

Introduction

What is happiness, exactly? How do we quantify it? Can you purchase happiness with money? Is pleasure determined by freedom or social support? Is it possible to define health as happiness? While these are contentious concerns, let us attempt to address them using a data-driven method utilizing the World Happiness Report 2021. The World Happiness Report is a remarkable assessment of global happiness. Happiness indices are increasingly being used by governments, businesses, and civil society to influence policy decisions and illustrate how well-being evaluations may be used to analyze a countrys progress.

Data

Data Source

Ajaypal Singh. World Happiness Report 2021. kaggle.com
https://www.kaggle.com/ajaypalsinghlo/world-happiness-report-2021 (accessed Feb 17, 2022).

Data Collection

The happiness scores and rankings use data from the Gallup World Poll which adopted the Cantrils Ladder of Life Scale as an assessment for well-being. Since 2012, Gallups World Poll has published eight happiness reports. It asks of respondents:
Please imagine a ladder with steps numbered from zero at the bottom to 10 at the top. The top of the ladder represents the best possible life for you and the bottom of the ladder represents the worst possible life for you. On which step of the ladder would you say you personally feel you stand at this time? (ladder-present) On which step do you think you will stand about five years from now? (ladder-future)

Cases

The poll is conducted for 149 countries across the world. Each observation/row in a data set represents a country.

Variables

There are total 20 variables in a dataset. But for the pourpose of this analysis, we can focus only on following variables:
Ladder Score : Happiness Index (0 - 10)
Logged GDP per capita
Social support
Healthy life expectancy
Freedom to make life choices
Generosity
Perceptions of corruption
The author has created columns for a hypothetical country Dystopia, that has values equal to the worlds lowest national averages for each of the six factors. They have no impact on the total score reported for each country. Hence those columns are not taken into consideration in this project.

Type of study

It is an observational study (poll).

Hypothesis testing:

Hypothesis 1

Most of the countries in Western Europe, North America and ANZ (call it group North) are well-developed but there is a huge diversity in terms of income in Asian, African and Middle East countries (call it group South). Lets check if variance of happiness index in group South is greater than that of group North.
2n = Variance of happiness index in group North
2s = Variance of happiness index in group South
H0: 2s = 2n
HA: 2s > 2n

Test Statistic

Variance of happiness index between group North and group South.

Reference Distribution

F-distribution can be used to make an inference on the Variances of two normal distribution because:
1) Poll is taken from different individuals from different contries, hence the sample is independent.
2) There is no clear outlier in the happiness index variable of either groups, the values are normally distributed.

grpNorth <- subset(happiness_report, happiness_report$region == "Western Europe" | happiness_report$region == "North America and ANZ")
head(grpNorth,3)
##       country         region ladder_score gdp_per_cpt social_support
## 1     Finland Western Europe        7.842      10.775          0.954
## 2     Denmark Western Europe        7.620      10.933          0.954
## 3 Switzerland Western Europe        7.571      11.117          0.942
##   healthy_life_exp freedom generosity corruption
## 1             72.0   0.949     -0.098      0.186
## 2             72.7   0.946      0.030      0.179
## 3             74.4   0.919      0.025      0.292
grpSouth <- subset(happiness_report, happiness_report$region == "South Asia" | happiness_report$region == "Sub-Saharan Africa" | happiness_report$region == "Middle East and North Africa")
head(grpSouth, 3)
##                 country                       region ladder_score gdp_per_cpt
## 12               Israel Middle East and North Africa        7.157      10.575
## 22              Bahrain Middle East and North Africa        6.647      10.669
## 25 United Arab Emirates Middle East and North Africa        6.561      11.085
##    social_support healthy_life_exp freedom generosity corruption
## 12          0.939           73.503   0.800      0.031      0.753
## 22          0.862           69.495   0.925      0.089      0.722
## 25          0.844           67.333   0.932      0.074      0.589
var.test(grpNorth$ladder_score, grpSouth$ladder_score, alternative = "two.sided")
## 
##  F test to compare two variances
## 
## data:  grpNorth$ladder_score and grpSouth$ladder_score
## F = 0.49921, num df = 24, denom df = 59, p-value = 0.06284
## alternative hypothesis: true ratio of variances is not equal to 1
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.2647113 1.0394510
## sample estimates:
## ratio of variances 
##          0.4992146

The p-value of F-test is 0.06284 which is greater than the significance level 0.05. In conclusion, there is no significant difference between the two variances. Hence we fail to reject the NULL hypothesis H0: 2a = 2n.

Hypothesis 2

Lets verify if mean happiness index in group North is greater than that of group south.
e: mean happiness index of group North
a: mean happiness index of group South
H0: n - s = 0
HA: n - s > 0

Test Statistic

Difference in the sample means of happiness score between group North and group South in 2021.

Reference Distribution

When small samples are taken, we assume that the populations are normally distributed and base our hypotheses tests on the t distribution. In this example, t-distribution can be used to make an inference because:
1) Poll is taken from different individuals from different contries, hence the sample is independent.
2) There is no clear outlier in the happiness index variable of either groups, the values are normally distributed.

Since we failed to reject the null hypothesis in Hypothesis 1, we can perform pooled-t-test for hypothesis stated in Hypothesis 2.

t.test(grpNorth$ladder_score, grpSouth$ladder_score, alternative = "greater", paired = FALSE, var.equal = TRUE, conf.level = 0.95)
## 
##  Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  grpNorth$ladder_score and grpSouth$ladder_score
## t = 11.933, df = 83, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is greater than 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  1.94087     Inf
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  6.949080  4.693833

Since p-value is less than 0.05, we reject null hypothesis. Hence we can say that group North has higher happiness index than that of group South in 2021.

Multiple Regression

Since our model has more than one predictor variable and one response, we can use multiple regression model
Y =0 + 11 + 22 + kk + 

model <- lm(happiness_report$ladder_score~happiness_report$gdp_per_cpt+happiness_report$social_support+happiness_report$healthy_life_exp+happiness_report$freedom+happiness_report$generosity+happiness_report$corruption)
summary(model)

## F-statistic: 73.27 on 6 and 142 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

F-statistic is a good indicator of whether there is a relationship between our predictor and the response variables. The further the F-statistic is from 1 the better it is. In our example the F-statistic is 73.27 which is relatively larger than 1 given the size of our data.

It can also be seen that p-value is < 2.2e-16, which is highly significant. This means that, at least, one of the predictor variables is significantly related to the outcome variable. From the coefficients table, it seems that Social support and freedom are the most significant attributes.

R-squared is an important measures of how well our model predicts the desired response variable which is equal to 0.7558 in our case. This value means that combination of GDP per capita, social support, healthy life expectancy, freedom of expression, generosity and corruption explain 75.58% of the variability in happiness score.

The R-squared value remains almost same but the value of F-statistic has notably increased. 

par(mfrow = c(2,2))
plot(pca_model)

Graph 1 is called as fitted vs residual plot. The red line is quite flat, in fact, the points are compact and look like a cloud of points. Hence linearity assumptions is met.
Graph 2 is known as QQ plot. The Y-axis is ordered, observed and standardized residuals. X-axis has ordered theoretical residuals. The points should fall roughly on the diagonal line and they do. Hence the assumption about the normal distribution of errors is also met.
Graph 3 and 4 also indicate linearity and almost constant variance.

Conclusion:

Multiple linear regression suggests that family support and freedom of expression are the most important factors to consider when determining happiness. Despite the numerous disagreements, it appears that happiness is also strongly linked to wealth. Nations with high happiness scores are also economically prosperous. Even though it is not mentioned in this survey, demography should, in my opinion, play a role in determining happiness. In the future, it would be fascinating to investigate the impact of this characteristics on happiness, as well as track how the data changes over time.
